quran[26]{c,v,t,f}:
37,77,"and made his offspring the only ones to survive, {1}",footnotes:1:This can have two meanings.
37,78,"and We established for him a good name among posterity."
37,79,"Peace be upon Noah among all the nations. {1}",footnotes:1:That is there is none in the world today
37,80,"Thus do We reward all those who do good."
37,81,"Surely he was one of Our truly believing servants."
37,82,"Thereafter We caused the others to be drowned."
37,83,"Abraham was on the self-same way (as Noah)."
37,84,"When he came to his Lord with a pure heart, {1}",footnotes:1:“Approached his Lord”: Turned to his Lord sincerely and exclusively; “with a sound heart”: With a heart that was free from all kinds of moral evils and weaknesses of faith
37,85,"and said to his father and his people: {1} “Whom do you worship?",footnotes:1:For further details of this story of the Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him)
37,86,"Is it false deities that you want to serve rather than Allah?"
37,87,"What do you think of the Lord of the whole Universe?” {1}",footnotes:1:That is
37,88,"Then {1} he looked carefully at the stars {2}",footnotes:1:The reference is to a particular incident the details of which have been given in(Surah Al-Anbiya
37,89,"and said: “I am sick.” {1}",footnotes:1:This is one of those three things concerning which it is said that the Prophet Abraham had told three lies in his life
37,90,"So turning their backs, they went away from him. {1}",footnotes:1:This sentence by itself shows the real state of the affairs. It appears that the people might be going to some fair of theirs. The family of the Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) might have also asked him to accompany them. He might have excused himself
37,91,"Then he went quietly to the (temple of the deities) and said: “What is the matter with you, why do you not eat? {1}",footnotes:1:This shows that there were different kinds of food placed before the idols in the temple.
37,92,"What is the matter with you, why do you not speak?”"
37,93,"Then he turned upon them, striking them with his right hand,"
37,94,"whereupon people came to him running. {1}",footnotes:1:Here the story has been told in brief. According to the details given in Surah Al-Anbiya
37,95,"Abraham said to them: “Do you worship what you yourselves have carved with your own hands"
37,96,"while it is Allah Who has created you and all that you make?”"
37,97,"They spoke among themselves: “Build him a pyre and then throw him into the furnace.”"
37,98,"They had contrived an evil plan against him, but We abased them all. {1}",footnotes:1:The words in( Surah Al-Anbiya
37,99,"Abraham said: {1} “I am going to my Lord; {2} He will guide me.",footnotes:1:The Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) said these words on his departure after he had been delivered safe from the fire and had decided to leave the country.|180743:It mean: I am leaving my home and country for the sake of Allah
37,100,"Lord, grant me a righteous son.” {1}",footnotes:1:This prayer by itself shows that the Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) at that time was childless. From the details given at other places in the Quran
37,101,"(In response to this prayer) We gave him the good news of a prudent boy; {1}",footnotes:1:From this one should not understand that this good news was given to him immediately following his prayer. In the Quran itself
37,102,"and when he was old enough to go about and work with him, (one day) Abraham said to him: “My son, I see in my dream that I am slaughtering you. {1} So consider (and tell me) what you think.” {2} He said: “Do as you are bidden. {3} You will find me, if Allah so wills, among the steadfast.”",footnotes:1:One should note that the Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) had dreamed that he was sacrificing his son and not that he had sacrificed him. Although at that time he understood the dream to mean that he should sacrifice his son and on that very basis
